\begin{abstract}
We report 537 new photometric candidates to be Quasars (hereafter QSOs) in an area
of 2.5 sq deg for the survey 10-years in celestial equator. The survey was carried out
during 1998 to 2008 with observations obtained
with the QUEST mosaic camera at the 1 m Schmidt telescope at the 
Venezuela National Observatory of Llano del Hato. The area studied
is part of a photometric catalog in the bands
V, R, I Johnson and contains approximately nine
million point sources  in $\sim1080 $ sq deg in the celestial equator (\citet{b2}). QSOs sample
was selected using criteria variability in every filter and the first-order
structure functions (\citet{b1}). Part of this region is covered by Sloan Digital 
Sky Survey (SDSS) and we
recover our criteria QSOs spectrocopically reported by the Data Release 9 (DR9). From a homogeneous sample of QSOs candidates,
we expect to detect about 870480 photometric candidates to QSOs in the entire 
catalog and regions not covered so far by SDSS.
\end{abstract}

\begin{keywords}
quasars: point objects -- surveys -- variability.
\end{keywords}

\section{Introduction}

The catalog of the variability survey of Centro de Investigaciones de Astronom\'ia (CVS-CIDA)
contains photometric data in the filters V, R, I of $\sim 9\times10^6$ point
sources (\citet{b2}), these data correspond to multiepoch observations for
10 years (1998-2008). The catalog covers a total 
area of 1080 square degrees in the celestial equatorial between: $60\textordmasculine \leq \alpha_{J2000} \leq 150 \textordmasculine$ 
and $\delta_{J200}=\pm 6\textordmasculine $, this is illustrated in Figure \ref{distribution}. With 
the information in this catalog the following has been studied: (\emph{i}) part of the thin and thick disk (\citet{b5})
of the Milky Way (MW), stellar streams structures in the halo of the 
MW at high and low galactic latitudes with the variability 
survey of RR Lyrae stars (\citet{b4}, \citet{b6}), (\emph{ii}) the variability survey of Orion OB1 (\citet{b7}, \citet{b8}), 
(\emph{iii}) Disk Evolution in the Orion OB1 Association (\citet{b9}), 
(\emph{iv}) Early stages in the evolution of protoplanetary disks (\citet{b10}),
(\emph{v}) a Large-Scale Optical-Near Survey for Brown Dwarfs and Very Low
Mass Stars in the Orion OB1 Association (\citet{b11}). However, despite the sheer
quality of this work and its scientific importance, in the area of 
extragalactic astronomy (particularly in the search for QSOs), this region
of the sky has not been fully studied in depth and the CVS-CIDA has not
been analyzed with this focus.\\

We now propose a census of photometric candidates 
to QSOs in the CVS-CIDA, which combine the search criteria of QSOs by 
periodic variability (\citet{b1}) with the intrinsic variability proposed by \citet{b12}, 
we analyzed 2.5 sq deg of the CVS-CIDA, between: $85\textordmasculine \leq \alpha_{J2000} \leq 87.5\textordmasculine$ 
and $-1.5\textordmasculine \leq \delta_{J2000} \leq -0.5\textordmasculine$.
The technique used 14,719 point sources has enabled the selection
of an initial sample of 537 sources which do not show periodic variability.
Our method shows effectiveness of 10 percent to recover QSOs reported
by SDSS DR9, in the areas where both scans overlap ($\sim$1.5 sq deg). In
future works, we will conduct a spectroscopic survey of 537 candidates to 
QSOs, this survey will be in the 1m Schmidt telescope located at the 
Venezuelan National Astronomical Observatory, Llano del Hato, M\'erida, 
Venezuela. This telescope is equipped with a 3.4$\textordmasculine$ 
objetive-prism (reciprocal dispersion $\sim$ 25 \AA{} arcsec$^{-1}$ in 
H$_{\alpha}$ at rest, \citet{b13}) and a 4$\times$4 CCD mosaic 
covering $2.3\textordmasculine \times 3.5\textordmasculine$
on the sky. The CCDs are 2048 $\times$ 2048 LORAL devises with 15$\mu$m pixels.
We classify the sample into two groups: the first group whose
spectra are consistent with the known spectrum of QSOs and the second
group consists of those sources whose spectra do not match those of QSOs.\\


