\subsection{First criterion: Variability}

The variability criterion considers whether each point
source CVS-CIDA presents periodic or aperiodic 
changes in its brightness over time. This 
variation is measured by the index of variability ($V_{Index}$), and
is given by the sum of the number times ($N_0$) the
brightness of each source was measured over the maximum number ($N_t$)
of times a source was measured about 3 arcmin around the source of interest
in each filter and weighted by the 
variability of probability $P(\chi^2_{\nu})$ in each filter.

\begin{equation}
V_{Index}\equiv(\frac{\sum^3_{j=1}\left(N_{0}/N_{T}\right)_{j}\times P(\chi^2_{\nu})_{j}}
{\sum^3_{j=1}\left(N_{0}/N_{T}\right)_{j}}\right) \times 100, 
\label{eq1}
\end{equation}

 With $j=1,2,3$ as the index over the three different filters used in the
survey ($V,R,I$). The individual $P(\chi^2_{\nu})_{j}$ values in the 
CVS-CIDA were calculated using the same methods used in 
\citet{b3}, ie. using the $\chi^2$ probability function.
In the CVS-CIDA all sources with $[P(\chi^2_{\nu})_{j} \leq 0.001]$
has a 99\% confidence level of being variable.


The equation \ref{eq1} is similar to the global confidence
level (GCL) used by \citet{b1} to select the sample of 
QSOs. We applied this equation iteratively on 14,719 point sources (green are in
Figure \ref{distribution}) corresponding to the region of interest 
(2.5 sq deg). Figure \ref{index} shows the cumulative
frequency distribution of the 
$V_{Index}$ for 14,719 point sources. We selected all sources with a 
$V_{Index} \geq 66.5$, reducing the initial sample by 81.81\%, recovering 
2678 possible candidates for QSOs. The $V_{Index}=66.5$ was
fixed at that value, since it is to be consistent with 
values of $V_{Index}$ of QSOs reported in the SDSS-DR9 
and recovered by our survey. This parameter ($V_{Index}$) is an 
important factor that allows a first filter in the 
total sample, separating the sources which are not variable,
regarding sources having a high $V_{Index}$. 

\subsection{Second criterion: Variability}

The second criterion is directly related to the time series
of observations of each point source of CVS-CIDA. The following
equations are similar to those used by \citet{b1}, except
the equation \ref{eq2}  that is weighty
($N_{0}/N_{T}$), see this in more detail in 
figure 5 of the article of \citet{b6}.


\begin{equation}
V_{j}\equiv\frac{\sum^3_j \left(N_{0}/N_{T}\right)_{j}\times\left(\sigma_{T}/\sigma_j\right)^2}{\sum^3_{j}\left(N_{0}/N_{T}\right)_{j}},
\label{eq2}
\end{equation}

In the equation \ref{eq2}, $\sigma_{T}$ is the total standard deviation



\begin{equation}
\Delta m_{j}=\frac{\sigma_{T}}{\Delta \langle m \rangle_{\rm{max}}}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
Q_{i}\equiv\frac{\sum^3_{j}\left(N_{0}/N_{T}\right)_{j}\times \left(V_{j}/\Delta m_{j}\right)}{\sum^3_j\left(N_{0}/N_{T}\right)_{j}}           
\end{equation}



